for the [[Central Comets]] in the [[Queensland Cup]].<ref name=\"Williams eyes off an NRL start at broncos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/story/2009/01/07/williams-eyes-off-an-nrl-start-at-broncos|title=Williams eyes off an NRL start at broncos|publisher=The Morning Bulletin|date=7 January 2009|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2011, Williams left [[Central Comets]] and moved to France where he captained [[Toulouse Olympique]]. In 2013 he returned to [[Central Comets]] now renamed [[Central Queensland Capras]] and went on to captain the side as well as play for them in over 150 games in his two spells. \n\n==Post playing==\nWilliams previously worked at The Morning Bulletin in Rockhampton as a sports journalist.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090912013742/http://www.broncos.com.au/default.aspx?s=player-profile-display&id=1645&team=Broncos&guy-williams Brisbane Broncos profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091003041521/http://comets.com.au/this-season/player-list/guy-williams/ Central Comets profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Guy}}\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league centres]]\n[[Category:Rugby league five-eighths]]\n[[Category:Toulouse Olympique players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league locks]]\n[[Category:Central Queensland Capras players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league second-rows]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "use same link throughout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guy_Williams_(rugby_league)"}
{"title_page": "Vidadala Rajini", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = \n| image               = Vidadala_Rajini_.jpg\n| office              = Member of Legislative Assembly, Chilakaluripeta (Guntur), Andhra Pradesh\n| predecessor         = Prathipati Pulla Rao\n| website             = https://www.vidadalarajini.com/\n| birth_date          = June 24, 1988\n| termstart1          = 1 June, 2019\n| termend1            = 31 May, 2024\n}}\n\nVidadala Rajini is a Politician and a [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|Member of Legislative Assembly]] from [[Chilakaluripet (Assembly constituency)|Chilakaluripeta (Assembly Constituency)]] in the Indian state of [[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/elections/andhra-pradesh-assembly-election-result-full-list-of-winners-mla/1585284/|title=Andhra Pradesh Assembly election result: Full list of winners|date=2019-05-23|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. She contested her first election to [[Andhra Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] in the year 2019 as a [[YSR Congress Party]] Candidate and won the seat by defeating the [[Telugu Desam Party|TDP]] Candidate [[Prathipati Pulla Rao]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/assembly-elections-2019/andhra-pradesh/chilakaluripet-election-result-s01a096/|title=Chilakaluripet Assembly Election Results 2019 Live: Chilakaluripet Constituency (Seat) Election Results, Live News.|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jonathan|first=P. Samuel|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/ysrcp-fields-bc-candidates-in-crucial-guntur-segments/article26572955.ece|title=YSRCP fields BC candidates in crucial Guntur segments|date=2019-03-19|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/history-has-it-that-women-from-guntur-make-most-of-their-chances/articleshow/68568684.cms|title=History has it that women from Guntur make most of their chances {{!}} Vijayawada News - Times of India|last=Mar 26|first=Samdani MN {{!}} TNN {{!}}|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=04:06}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = \n| image               = Vidadala_Rajini_.jpg\n| office              = Member of Legislative Assembly, Chilakaluripeta (Guntur), Andhra Pradesh\n| predecessor         = Prathipati Pulla Rao\n| website             = https://www.vidadalarajini.com/\n| birth_date          = June 24, 1988\n| termstart1          = 1 June, 2019\n| termend1            = 31 May, 2024\n}}\n\nVidadala Rajini is a Politician and a [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|Member of Legislative Assembly]] from [[Chilakaluripet (Assembly constituency)|Chilakaluripeta (Assembly Constituency)]] in the Indian state of [[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/elections/andhra-pradesh-assembly-election-result-full-list-of-winners-mla/1585284/|title=Andhra Pradesh Assembly election result: Full list of winners|date=2019-05-23|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. She contested her first election to [[Andhra Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] in the year 2019 as a [[YSR Congress Party]] Candidate and won the seat by defeating the [[Telugu Desam Party|TDP]] Candidate [[Prathipati Pulla Rao]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/assembly-elections-2019/andhra-pradesh/chilakaluripet-election-result-s01a096/|title=Chilakaluripet Assembly Election Results 2019 Live: Chilakaluripet Constituency (Seat) Election Results, Live News.|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jonathan|first=P. Samuel|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/ysrcp-fields-bc-candidates-in-crucial-guntur-segments/article26572955.ece|title=YSRCP fields BC candidates in crucial Guntur segments|date=2019-03-19|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/history-has-it-that-women-from-guntur-make-most-of-their-chances/articleshow/68568684.cms|title=History has it that women from Guntur make most of their chances {{!}} Vijayawada News - Times of India|last=Mar 26|first=Samdani MN {{!}} TNN {{!}}|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20|last3=Ist|first3=04:06}}</ref>\n", "name_user": "Navneet.rishi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vidadala_Rajini"}
{"title_page": "Sir Robert Maude, 1st Baronet", "text_new": "'''Sir Robert Maude, 1st Baronet''' (1677 \u2013 4 August 1750) was an [[Anglo-Irish]] politician.\n\nMaude sat in the [[Irish House of Commons]] as the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Gowran (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Gowran]] from 1703 to 1713. Between 1713 and 1727 he represented [[St Canice (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|St Canice]], before sitting for [[Bangor (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Bangor]] from 1727 to his death in 1750.<ref>E. M. Johnston-Liik, [https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/MPs_in_Dublin.html?id=jitdluWSybIC ''MPs in Dublin: Companion to History of the Irish Parliament, 1692-1800''] (Ulster Historical Foundation, 2006), p.106 (Retrieved 20 April 2020).</ref> On 9 May 1705 he had been created a [[baronet]], of Dundrum in the [[Baronetage of Ireland]], and was succeeded in his title by his son, [[Thomas Maude, 1st Baron de Montalt|Thomas Maude]], who was made [[Baron de Montalt]] in 1776.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Gowran (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Gowran]]\n | with = [[Patrick Wemyss]]\n | years  = 1703-1713\n | before = [[Edward May (politician)|Edward May]] <br/> [[Joseph Stepney]]\n | after  = [[Sir Richard Levinge, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Levinge, Bt]] <br/> [[James Agar (1672\u20131733)|James Agar]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Canice (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|St Canice]]\n | with = [[Sir Standish Hartstonge, 2nd Baronet|Sir Standish Hartstonge, Bt]]\n | years  = 1713-1727\n | before = [[Richard Connell (Irish politician)|Richard Connell]] <br/> [[Richard Cole (politician)|Richard Cole]]\n | after  = [[James Agar (1672\u20131733)|James Agar]] <br/> [[Richard Dawson (died 1766)|Richard Dawson]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bangor (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Bangor]]\n | with = [[Acheson Moore]]\n | years  = 1727-1750\n | before = [[Michael Ward (Irish politician)|Michael Ward]] <br/> [[Acheson Moore]]\n | after  = Mathew Forde <br/> [[Acheson Moore]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|ie-bt}}\n{{s-new | creation}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Viscount Hawarden|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Dundrum)''' | years=1705\u20131850}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Thomas Maude, 1st Baron de Montalt|Thomas Maude]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maude, Robert, 1st Baronet}}\n[[Category:1677 births]]\n[[Category:1750 deaths]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Irish people]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1703\u20131713]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1713\u20131714]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1715\u20131727]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1727\u20131760]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Down constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Kilkenny constituencies]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Robert Maude, 1st Baronet''' (1677 \u2013 4 August 1750) was an [[Anglo-Irish]] politician.\n\nMaude sat in the [[Irish House of Commons]] as the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Gowran (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Gowran]] from 1703 to 1713. Between 1713 and 1727 he represented [[St Canice (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|St Canice]], before sitting for [[Bangor (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Bangor]] from 1727 to his death in 1750.<ref>E. M. Johnston-Liik, [https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/MPs_in_Dublin.html?id=jitdluWSybIC ''MPs in Dublin: Companion to History of the Irish Parliament, 1692-1800''] (Ulster Historical Foundation, 2006), p.106 (Retrieved 20 April 2020).</ref> On 9 May 1705 he had been created a [[baronet]], of Dundrum in the [[Baronetage of Ireland]], and was succeeded in his title by his son, [[Thomas Maude, 1st Baron de Montalt|Thomas Maude]], who was made [[Baron de Montalt]] in 1776.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie}}\n{{succession box\n | title  =